9 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]]\n| '''W''' 25\u201323\n| 4\u20135\n| Land Shark Stadium\n| [http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2009111501/2009/REG10/buccaneers@dolphins Recap]\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#cfc;\"\n! 11\n| November 19\n| at [[2009 Carolina Panthers season|Carolina Panthers]]\n| '''W''' 24\u201317\n| 5\u20135\n| [[Bank of America Stadium]]\n| [http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2009111900/2009/REG11/dolphins@panthers Recap]\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#fcc;\"\n! 12\n| November 29\n| at '''[[2009 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]]'''\n| '''L''' 14\u201331\n| 5\u20136\n| [[Ralph Wilson Stadium]]\n| [http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2009112901/2009/REG12/dolphins@bills Recap]\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#cfc;\"\n! 13\n| December 6\n| '''[[2009 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]]'''\n| '''W''' 22\u201321\n| 6\u20136\n| Land Shark Stadium\n| [http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2009120613/2009/REG13/patriots@dolphins Recap]\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#cfc;\"\n! 14\n| December 13\n| at [[2009 Jacksonville Jaguars season|Jacksonville Jaguars]]\n| '''W''' 14\u201310\n| 7\u20136\n| [[Jacksonville Municipal Stadium]]\n| [http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2009121305/2009/REG14/dolphins@jaguars Recap]\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#fcc;\"\n! 15\n| December 20\n| at [[2009 Tennessee Titans season|Tennessee Titans]]\n| '''L''' 24\u201327 {{small|(OT)}}\n| 7\u20137\n| [[LP Field]]\n| [http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2009122008/2009/REG15/dolphins@titans Recap]\n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#fcc;\"\n! 16\n| December 27\n| [[2009 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]]\n| '''L''' 20\u201327\n| 7\u20138\n| Land Shark Stadium\n| [http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2009122704/2009/REG16/texans@dolphins Recap] \n|-  style=\"text-align:center; background:#fcc;\"\n! 17\n| January 3\n| [[2009 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]]\n| '''L''' 24\u201330\n| 7\u20139\n| Land Shark Stadium\n| [http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2010010306/2009/REG17/steelers@dolphins Recap]\n|}\n\n===Standings===\n{{2009 AFC East standings}}\n\n===Game results===\n\n====Week 1: at Atlanta Falcons====\n{{Americanfootballbox|\n|Road=Dolphins\n|R1=0||R2=0||R3=0||R4=7||RT=7\n|Home='''Falcons'''\n|H1=0||H2=10||H3=6||H4=3||HT=19\n|stadium= [[Georgia Dome]], [[Atlanta]]\n|time= 1:00&nbsp;pm [[Eastern Time Zone|EDT]]\n|weather= None (Domed Stadium)\n|attendance= 67,606\n|referee= [[Walt Coleman]]\n|TV=[[NFL on CBS|CBS]] |TVAnnouncers= [[Greg Gumbel]] & [[Dan Dierdorf]]\n}}\n[[Image:2009 Miami Dolphins.jpg|thumb|right|The Miami Dolphins preparing for the 2009 season opener in Atlanta.]]\n\nAfter a great season for the [[Miami Dolphins]] in 2008, the Dolphins went to the Georgia Dome to take on 2008 playoff contenders, the [[Atlanta Falcons]].\nAfter a scoreless first quarter, the Falcons got on the board with a 1-yard touchdown pass from [[Matt Ryan (American football)|Matt Ryan]] to fullback [[Ovie Mughelli]] in the second quarter. They also got a 36-yard field goal by kicker [[Jason Elam]] to make the score 10\u20130 at halftime. In the third quarter, [[Mike Peterson]] intercepted a [[Chad Pennington]] pass, which set up a 20-yard touchdown pass to tight end [[Tony Gonzalez]] and a 50-yard field goal by Jason Elam to make the score 19\u20130. Chad Pennington then hit a 9-yard touchdown pass to [[Ricky Williams]].\n\nThe Falcons won the game 19\u20137 as the Dolphins started their season 0\u20131.\n\nIn 2008, no other team turned the ball over less than the Dolphins with only 13 turnovers, but in Week 1 Miami's offense had 4 turnovers, without having a single turnover on defense.\n\n====Week 2: vs. Indianapolis Colts====\n{{Americanfootballbox|\n|Road='''Colts'''\n|R1=7||R2=6||R3=0||R4=14||RT=27\n|Home=Dolphins\n|H1=7||H2=6||H3=0||H4=10||HT=23\n|stadium= [[Land Shark Stadium]], [[Miami Gardens, Florida]]\n|time= 8:30&nbsp;pm [[Eastern Time Zone|EDT]]\n|weather= 84 \u00b0F (Cloudy)\n|attendance= 66,227\n|referee= [[Terry McAulay]]\n|TV=[[Monday Night Football|ESPN]] |TVAnnouncers= [[Mike Tirico]], [[Ron Jaworski]], [[Jon Gruden]], & [[Suzy Kolber]]\n}}\nAfter a miserable loss to the [[Atlanta Falcons]], the Dolphins host their home opener to the [[Indianapolis Colts]]. On the first play from scrimmage, [[Peyton Manning]] threw an 80-yard touchdown pass to tight end [[Dallas Clark]]. The Dolphins answered with a 14-yard touchdown run by [[Ronnie Brown]] out of the [[Wildcat Offense]]. The Dolphins and Colts kept going back and forth at each other with two field goals by [[Dan Carpenter]] and [[Adam Vinatieri]] to make the score 13\u201313 at halftime. After a scoreless third quarter, Ronnie Brown ran 2-yards for a touchdown to put Miami up 20\u201313. The Colts answered back with a 15-yard touchdown run by rookie running back [[Donald Brown (American football)|Donald Brown]]. Miami than hit a 45-yard field goal by Dan Carpenter. But the Colts took the lead thanks to a 48-yard touchdown pass to [[Pierre Gar\u00e7on]]. The Dolphins tried to rally at the end of the game but [[Chad Pennington]] was intercepted by [[Antoine Bethea]] to secure the Colts' victory.\n\nThe Colts won the game 27\u201323 as the Dolphins dropped to 0\u20132.\n\nThe Dolphins dominated the game in the time of possession battle, but lost the game with almost 50 minutes of offensive possession.\n\n====Week 3: at San Diego Chargers====\n{{Americanfootballbox|\n|Road=Dolphins\n|R1=0||R2=3||R3=3||R4=7||RT=20\n|Home='''Chargers'''\n|H1=0||H2=3||H3=7||H4=13||HT=23\n|stadium= [[Qualcomm Stadium]], [[San Diego, California]]\n|time= 4:15&nbsp;pm [[Eastern Time Zone|EDT]]\n|weather= 80 \u00b0F (Sunny)\n|attendance= 67,230\n|referee= [[Bill Leavy]]\n|TV=[[NFL on CBS|CBS]] |TVAnnouncers= [[Dick Enberg]] & [[Dan Fouts]]\n}}\nLooking for their first win of the season, the Dolphins traveled to [[Qualcomm Stadium]] to take on the [[San Diego Chargers]].\n\nAfter a scoreless first quarter, [[Nate Kaeding]] hit a 25-yard field goal to score the first points of the game. Miami answered with a 24-yard field goal to tie the game at halftime 3\u20133. Miami took the lead after a 23-yard field goal by [[Dan Carpenter]]. But the Chargers retook the lead with a 5-yard touchdown run by [[Philip Rivers]]. The Chargers pulled away in the fourth quarter with two Nate Kaeding field goals and a 31-yard interception return by safety [[Eric Weddle]]. The Dolphins got a 14-yard touchdown run by [[Ricky Williams]], but couldn't make a comeback.\n\nThe Chargers won the game 23\u201313 as the Dolphins fell to 0\u20133.\n\nDolphins quarterback [[Chad Pennington]] left the game with a shoulder injury after being hit by linebacker [[Kevin Burnett]] and was out for the season. The Dolphins chose [[Chad Henne]] to lead the Dolphins for the rest of the season.\n\n====Week 4: vs. Buffalo Bills====\n{{Americanfootballbox|\n|Road=Bills\n|R1=0||R2=3||R3=0||R4=7||RT=10\n|Home='''Dolphins'''\n|H1=0||H2=17||H3=14||H4=7||HT=38\n|stadium= [[Land Shark Stadium]], [[Miami Gardens, Florida]]\n|time= 4:05&nbsp;pm [[Eastern Time Zone|EDT]]\n|weather= 88 \u00b0F (Sunny)\n|attendance= 65,523\n|referee= [[Carl Cheffers]]\n|TV=[[NFL on CBS|CBS]] |TVAnnouncers= [[Kevin Harlan]] & [[Solomon Wilcots]]\n}}\nThe [[Miami Dolphins]] came off of a 0\u20133 start and tried to rebound against the [[Buffalo Bills]]. After a scoreless first quarter the Dolphins rallied quick with a 23-yard interception return for a touchdown by rookie [[Vontae Davis]] and a 1-yard touchdown run by [[Ronnie Brown]] along with a 33-yard field goal by [[Dan Carpenter]] making the halftime score 17\u20133. Miami continued with a [[Chad Henne]] touchdown pass to [[Brian Hartline]] and a 1-yard touchdown run by [[Ricky Williams]]. [[Trent Edwards]] hit [[Josh Reed]] for a 3-yard touchdown but Miami ended the game with a 1-yard touchdown run by Ronnie Brown.\n\nThe Dolphins won the game 38\u201310 as the team improved to 1\u20133.\n\nChad Henne made his first NFL start and threw for 115 yards and a touchdown.\n\n====Week 5: vs. New York Jets====\n{{Americanfootballbox|\n|Road=Jets\n|R1=7||R2=6||R3=0||R4=14||RT=0\n|Home='''Dolphins'''\n|H1=10||H2=0||H3=0||H4=21||HT=0\n|stadium= [[Land Shark Stadium]], [[Miami Gardens, Florida]]\n|time= 8:30&nbsp;pm [[Eastern Time Zone|EDT]]\n|weather= 83 \u00b0F (Clear)\n|attendance= 69,767\n|referee= [[Alberto Riveron]]\n|TV=[[Monday Night Football|ESPN]] |TVAnnouncers= [[Mike Tirico]], [[Ron Jaworski]], & [[Jon Gruden]]\n}}\nRonnie Brown ran in for the winning touchdown with just seconds left to send the Dolphins into their bye week at 2\u20133.\n\n====Week 6: BYE====\n\n====Week 7: vs. New Orleans Saints====\n{{Americanfootballbox|\n|Road='''Saints'''\n|R1=3||R2=7||R3=14||R4=22||RT=46\n|Home=Dolphins\n|H1=14||H2=10||H3=10||H4=0||HT=34\n|stadium= [[Land Shark Stadium]], [[Miami Gardens, Florida]]\n|time= 4:15&nbsp;pm EDT\n|weather= 89 \u00b0F (Sunny)\n|attendance= 66,689\n|referee= [[John Parry (American football official)|John Parry]]\n|TV=[[NFL on Fox|Fox]] |TVAnnouncers= [[Dick Stockton]], [[Charles Davis (defensive back)|Charles Davis]], & Jaime Maggio\n}}\nAfter they passed on signing him during the 2006 offseason, this was Saints quarterback [[Drew Brees]]' first time playing in Miami. With the surprising loss, the Dolphins dropped to 2\u20134.\n\n====Week 8: at New York Jets====\n{{Americanfootballbox|\n|Road='''Dolphins'''\n|R1=0||R2=3||R3=21||R4=6||RT=30\n|Home=Jets\n|H1=0||H2=3||H3=16||H4=6||HT=25\n|stadium= [[Giants Stadium|The Meadowlands]], [[East Rutherford, New Jersey]]\n|time= 1:00&nbsp;pm [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n|weather= 54 \u00b0F (Cloudy)\n|attendance= 77,531\n|referee= [[Don Carey (official)|Don Carey]]\n|TV=[[NFL on CBS|CBS]] |TVAnnouncers= [[Jim Nantz]] & [[Phil Simms]]\n}}\nWith their season sweep over the Jets, the Dolphins improved to 3\u20134.\n\n====Week 9: at New England Patriots====\n{{Americanfootballbox|\n|Road=Dolphins\n|R1=3||R2=7||R3=7||R4=0||RT=0\n|Home='''Patriots'''\n|H1=7||H2=9||H3=8||H4=3||HT=0\n|stadium= [[Gillette Stadium]], [[Foxborough, Massachusetts]]\n|time= 1:00&nbsp;pm [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n|weather= 65 \u00b0F (Sunny)\n|attendance= 68,756\n|referee= [[Mike Carey (American football)|Mike Carey]]\n|TV=[[NFL on CBS|CBS]] |TVAnnouncers= [[Greg Gumbel]] & [[Dan Dierdorf]]\n}}\nWith the loss, the Dolphins dropped to 3\u20135.\n\n====Week 10: vs. Tampa Bay Buccaneers====\n{{Americanfootballbox|\n|Road=Buccaneers\n|R1=3||R2=3||R3=3||R4=14||RT=23\n|Home='''Dolphins'''\n|H1=6||H2=13||H3=0||H4=6||HT=25\n|stadium= [[Land Shark Stadium]], [[Miami Gardens, Florida]]\n|time= 1:00&nbsp;pm [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n|weather= 80 \u00b0F (Sunny)\n|attendance= 66,085\n|referee= [[Tony Corrente]]\n|TV=[[NFL on Fox|Fox]] |TVAnnouncers= [[Ron Pitts]], [[John Lynch (American football)|John Lynch]], & [[Laura Okmin]]\n}}\nWith the win, the Dolphins improved to 4\u20135.\n\n====Week 11: at Carolina Panthers====\n{{Americanfootballbox|\n|Road='''Dolphins'''\n|R1=0||R2=14||R3=0||R4=10||RT=24\n|Home=Panthers\n|H1=3||H2=0||H3=0||H4=14||HT=17\n|stadium= [[Bank of America Stadium]], [[Charlotte, North Carolina]]\n|time= 8:20&nbsp;pm [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n|weather= 56 \u00b0F (Cloudy)\n|attendance= 73,475\n|referee= [[Walt Anderson (American football)|Walt Anderson]]\n|TV=[[NFL Network|NFLN]] |TVAnnouncers= [[Bob Papa]] & [[Matt Millen]]\n}}\nWith the win, the Dolphins improved to 5\u20135.\n\n====Week 12: at Buffalo Bills====\n{{Americanfootballbox|\n|Road=Dolphins\n|R1=0||R2=7||R3=7||R4=0||RT=14\n|Home='''Bills'''\n|H1=0||H2=7||H3=0||H4=24||HT=31\n|stadium= [[Ralph Wilson Stadium]], [[Orchard Park, New York]]\n|time= 1:00&nbsp;pm [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n|weather= 49 \u00b0F (Sunny)\n|attendance= 70,155\n|referee= [[Jeff Triplette]]\n|TV=[[CBS]] |TVAnnouncers= [[Gus Johnson (sportscaster)|Gus Johnson]] and [[Steve Tasker]]\n}}\nWith the loss, the Dolphins fell to 5\u20136.\n\n====Week 13: vs. New England Patriots====\n{{Americanfootballbox|\n|Road=Patriots\n|R1=7||R2=7||R3=7||R4=0||RT=21\n|Home='''Dolphins'''\n|H1=0||H2=10||H3=9||H4=3||HT=22\n|stadium= [[Land Shark Stadium]], [[Miami Gardens, Florida]]\n|time= 1:00&nbsp;pm [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n|weather= 75 \u00b0F (Clear)\n|attendance= 70,102\n|referee= [[Gene Steratore]]\n|TV=[[NFL on CBS|CBS]] |TVAnnouncers= [[Jim Nantz]] & [[Phil Simms]]\n}}\nWith the win, the Dolphins improved to 6\u20136.\n\n====Week 14: at Jacksonville Jaguars====\n{{Americanfootballbox|\n|Road='''Dolphins'''\n|R1=7||R2=7||R3=0||R4=0||RT=14\n|Home=Jaguars\n|H1=0||H2=7||H3=3||H4=0||HT=10\n|stadium= [[Jacksonville Municipal Stadium]], [[Jacksonville, Florida]]\n|time= 1:00&nbsp;pm [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n|weather= 75 \u00b0F (Sunny)\n|attendance= 60,457\n|referee= [[Walt Coleman]]\n|TV=[[CBS]] |TVAnnouncers= [[Kevin Harlan]] & [[Solomon Wilcots]]\n}}\nWith the win, the Dolphins improved to 7\u20136.\n\n====Week 15: at Tennessee Titans====\n{{Americanfootballbox|\n|Road=Dolphins\n|R1=3||R2=3||R3=3||R4=15||R5=0\n|Home='''Titans'''\n|H1=7||H2=10||H3=7||H4=0||H5=3\n|stadium= [[LP Field]], [[Nashville, Tennessee]]\n|time= 1:00&nbsp;pm [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n|weather= 35 \u00b0F (Cloudy)\n|attendance= 69,143\n|referee= [[Scott Green (American football official)|Scott Green]]\n|TV=[[CBS]] |TVAnnouncers= [[Dick Enberg]] & [[Dan Fouts]]\n}}\nWith the loss, the Dolphins dropped to 7\u20137.\n\n====Week 16: vs. Houston Texans====\n{{Americanfootballbox|\n|Road='''Texans'''\n|R1=10||R2=17||R3=0||R4=0|RT=27\n|Home=Dolphins\n|H1=0||H2=3||H3=7||H4=10|HT=20\n|stadium= [[Land Shark Stadium]], [[Miami Gardens, Florida]]\n|time= 1:00&nbsp;pm [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n|weather= 75 \u00b0F (Sunny)\n|attendance= 65,847\n|referee= [[Ron Winter]]\n|TV=[[CBS]] |TVAnnouncers= [[Ian Eagle]] & [[Rich Gannon]]\n}}\nWith the loss, the Dolphins dropped to 7\u20138.\n\n====Week 17: vs. Pittsburgh Steelers====\n{{Americanfootballbox|\n|Road='''Steelers'''\n|R1=14||R2=3||R3=7||R4=6|RT=\n|Home=Dolphins\n|H1=7||H2=3||H3=0||H4=14|HT=\n|stadium= [[Land Shark Stadium]], [[Miami Gardens, Florida]]\n|time=  1:00&nbsp;pm [[Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n|weather=  60 \u00b0F (Partly Cloudy)\n|attendance= 70,102\n|referee= [[Bill Leavy]]\n|TV=[[NFL on CBS|CBS]] |TVAnnouncers= [[Greg Gumbel]] & [[Dan Dierdorf]]\n}}\nThe final outcome of this game had somewhat of a [[domino effect]].  It resulted in the Dolphins' elimination from the post-season (including [[Super Bowl XLIV]], which they hosted February 8, 2010), and also, by virtue of the final standings' tiebreaker (as the result of the [[2009 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]] defeating the [[2009 Oakland Raiders season|Oakland Raiders]]), the Steelers themselves being dethroned of their world title defense.\n\nThe Dolphins ended their season in 3rd place in the AFC East as they finished the season 7\u20139.\n\n===Transactions===\n\n==Staff==\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"text-align: left;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"7\" style=\"background:#066; color:white; text-align:center;\"|'''Miami Dolphins 2009 staff'''\n|-\n|  style=\"font-size:95%; vertical-align:top;\"| '''Front Office'''\n*Chairman/Managing General Partner \u2013 [[Stephen M. Ross|Stephen Ross]]\n*CEO \u2013 [[Mike Dee]]\n*Vice Chairman \u2013 [[Don Shula]]\n*Executive Vice President of Football Operations \u2013 [[Bill Parcells]]\n*General Manager \u2013 [[Jeff Ireland]]\n*Assistant Director of Player Personnel \u2013 [[Brian Gaine]]\n*Director of College Scouting \u2013 Chris Grier\n\n'''Head Coaches'''\n*Head Coach \u2013 [[Tony Sparano]]\n*Assistant Head Coach/Secondary \u2013 [[Todd Bowles]]\n\n'''Offensive Coaches'''\n*Offensive Coordinator \u2013 [[Dan Henning]]\n*Quarterbacks \u2013 [[David Lee (coach)|David Lee]]\n*Running Backs \u2013 [[James Saxon (American football)|James Saxon]]\n*Wide Receivers \u2013 [[Karl Dorrell]]\n*Tight Ends \u2013 [[George DeLeone]]\n*Offensive Line \u2013